{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_016JZEGrb4vQc5D72fyKFG3F","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good, I can see the issue. The pods are cycling - readiness probes fail, causing kills, and starting new pods. The StatefulSet has `podManagementPolicy: OrderedReady`, so pod-1 won't start until pod-0 is ready, and pod-2 won't start until pod-1 is ready.\n\nThe key issues I can identify:\n1. `timeoutSeconds: 1` for both liveness and readiness probes - `mongosh` with authentication can take more than 1 second.\n2. `failureThreshold: 2` for the liveness probe - too low, kills the pod after just 2 failures.\n3. `initialDelaySeconds: 5` for the readiness probe is likely too short - MongoDB might not even be accepting connections yet.\n4. The liveness probe's `initialDelaySeconds: 15` could also be insufficient.\n\nThe readiness probe checks if the pod is PRIMARY or SECONDARY using `db.hello()`, but if the replica set hasn't been initialized, pods will be stuck in STARTUP state. The real problem is there's no initialization mechanism - no init container or job running `rs.initiate()` - so with `OrderedReady` policy, pod-0 starts first but remains in STARTUP, blocking the others from ever starting.\n\nLooking at the current state though, pods 0 and 1 are both Ready, and pod-2 just started 9 seconds ago, so maybe the replica set is already initialized and it's just recovering.\n\nThe real problem is those probe settings are way too aggressive—1 second timeout with a failure threshold of 2 means any hiccup during startup, load spikes, or when mongosh takes slightly longer causes failures. I need to check the actual replica set status and understand how the health user is configured.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2301,"cache_read_input_tokens":30558,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephem